animal.description: Are you looking for a friend, a pal, a comrade, a best bud? Hey! I’m a Buddy! I could be your best Buddy! We could hang out and do dude things—I mean, I am the rough-and-tumble sort! We could go the beach and scope out babes, or dudes, you know, whatever. I just want to hang out with you and be besties! I’m fun and adventurous, so an active lifestyle is right up my alley. I love alleys—they have so many interesting smells! I love to go for walks and take in the aromas of the world. I get along great with the other dogs here but try to boss around the more sensitive pooches in my playgroup, I will adore all the fun and attention that sturdy children 12+ have to offer, but I need a cat-free family that understands I lack some impulse control. A family savvy with herding breeds will be ideal! My crate training is going very well, and I know how to “sit” and “shake” when asked! I have so much to learn still and am hoping for a patient, committed, and energetic person to show me the ropes. Let’s see if we could be friends! You will never know another Buddy quite like me!

animal.description:
Barry Manilow may have been a thing of the 1980'sbut we have the new, improved and younger Barry and he is more than ready to croon away and win your heart and have you waving a lighter in the dark and singing songs of love and adoration towell most likely him! Barry is a totally Hollywood picture worthy Shepherd mix who is about a year old and weighs around 50 lbs full grown. Barry is a mostly blond guy with the typical black muzzle and a personality that is huge, both in terms of fun and energy as well as outgoing. He is definitely the social butterfly of any group. Barry is great with the other dogs, boys and girls alike and could easily fit into a home with another dog. He would love adventures and activity and would likely love to go just about anywhere with you, hoping to learn about the big wide world as well as the comfy home of you and yours. Barry can walk on a leash and is learning lots of things about crate training, proving to be smart as well as handsome. He is the total package and cannot wait to hop in the car and skedaddle on home with you ASAP!

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
Hello! My name is Miri, which is short for Miracle. I am a 5-year-old spayed female blue merle rough Collie, and I am looking for a very special family because I am a special needs dog. I am super sweet, fully vetted, housebroken and love hanging out with my foster mom and her fabulous Collie Casey. I usually spend my days lounging on my bed, sunning myself on the deck if the weather is good and doing typical Collie stuff like checking for crumbs on the floor. I'm not real active because when I was a little puppy I had a head injury but I need folks that will keep me moving with gentle walks. I have recently discovered the joys of T-touch. My foster mom has been studying T-touch on the Internet and she called Hope one morning and said, "Miri has awakened!" The stimulation of gentle hands all over me has made me feel alive! I don't let my disabilities stop me even though I am blind in my left eye, a little hard of hearing on that same side and I walk with a little shuffle. I would love a stay at home mom or dad, with a one-story house that is easy for me to navigate. I have a passion for eating, so I am on a low calorie diet with fresh veggies added. I also take thyroid meds every day and need a couple of drops in my eyes twice a day. Easy Peasy, huh? My foster mom says I blossom every day and make her smile, so I think I would make a great family member with your love and patience. But remember, I am not just a pretty face.

The first step toward any placement is a completed adoption application which you will find online at www.colliesheltierescue.org. Without a completed application, there is no place to start a conversation.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Dog for a day 1/25:

I enjoyed an active morning with Nitro. He's a beautiful dog with lots of energy and enthusiasm for just about everything and everyone in his path. He taught this small dog owner a thing or two about walking a larger, strong dog on a leash. Once I got the hang of it he was ready to play. Wasn't sure how affectionate he would be until I sat on the grass and he joyfully jumped on me for a minute until desperately wanting to find what might be in my backpack. His suspicion was correct. He enjoyed a quick treat and off we went. Nitro seemed most excited at the sight of children playing and he reacted well (stayed close and quiet) when small dogs lost their cool and barked at him. He's a good boy and loves to be praised. At the end of our walk I was a sweaty, muddy mess (did I mention he was playful?) and he looked at me with this priceless expression that seemed to say, "Thanks. You'll get the hang of this. Let's do it again some time." Check him out and see how he's even more gorgeous in person!

Nitro is a sweet boy he was found by some people who were driving after a storm. They posted him on the proper sites in hopes of finding his owner. He is a love bug, likes to cuddle, and is very playful. He love loves his ladies so he would do best in a home with females only as he is not comfortable with men. Although he does come around when given the time and reassurance. He loves to swim, play fetch, and give lots of kisses.

animal.description:
DOB: 8/2020 Weight: 36 lbs
This is Bella aka Boo Boo. Bella came into foster after her owner could no longer give her the proper care she needed. She's now available for adoption through PCPOUNDPUPPIES.
Bella is a 6 month old solid black lab mix currently weighing in at 36lbs. She's up to date on all her vaccinations and is scheduled to be spayed on 2-10-21. Bella has been working on her house training and is getting better with time. She does fine in the kennel with occasional barking if something interesting is happening. Bella loves food time and eats twice a day on an elevated feeder beside our other dog. She will sit for a treat and loves her hard chew toys. She is currently in foster with both a small and large dog and two cats. She does fine with kids too. Know that Bella has A LOT of energy and loves to walk and wrestle with other dogs. She also sheds quite a bit and will be in need of occasional brushing. Overall she'd make a perfect family pet, especially if there is another dog to play with. If interested contact PCPOUNDPUPPIES or fill out an application through their website.
Her fee is $150. We have a two week foster to adopt trial program where we can loan you a crate, leash and collar. ***YOU MUST FILL OUT AN APPLICATION BEFORE WE DO ANY MEET AND GREETS. QUESTIONS? CONTACT pcpoundpuppies1@gmail.com
Our adoption fee is $150 which covers a portion of the dog's vetting costs. The adoption process includes the completion of an application followed by an interview.
Click here to submit an adoption application: https://pcpoundpuppies.webs.com/adoption-application
***IMPORTANT: Due to the effects of COVID-19, our Sunday adoption events at Pet Food Center have been canceled until further notice. If there is a dog you are interested in meeting, be sure to contact us and we may be able to set up a meet and greet as soon as possible.***
You can get in touch with us by email at pcpoundpuppies1@gmail.com or by phone at 812-483-4341 for more information.
We respond to inquiries and adoption applications at our earliest opportunity, but please be patient with us as we work full-time jobs and perform this service as volunteers. We do our best to return messages and schedule adoption interviews within a couple of days of receiving your application.
The fastest way to get the ball rolling is to complete an adoption application for the dog that caught your eye. Thank you for considering the adoption of a shelter dog!

animal.description:
Chase is a 3 year old Australian Shepherd/Terrier mix who weighs 26 lbs. He’s a cute little guy who has one brown eye and one blue eye. He’s friendly and outgoing and would like to have a nice yard in which to run and play with his family.  He’s very sweet and friendly. 
We will add more information as we get to know him better. 
If you’d like to meet Chase, the first step is to complete and submit an adoption application on our okwestierescue.com website and we’ll get the process started. 
Please allow 1-2 weeks to finish processing your application, but please know our volunteers are working hard on it. 
Chase’s adoption fee is $300 and is tax deductible. 

NOTE: You must complete and submit an application and be approved to adopt prior to being able to meet the dog.  The requested tax-deductible adoption donation is $400 for our puppies, $300 for up to age 7 and $150 for ages 8 and older.
We do not ship our pets.  Be prepared to travel to Tulsa, OK, or Oklahoma City, OK, or the location where this dog is fostered to pick up your dog in person if your application is approved.  Once you are approved, you may adopt any of our dogs that is a good fit. 
We are a non-profit organization that spends our adoption fees and donations on vaccinations, surgeries, various medical tests, medicines, food and supplies needed by our dogs. Our fees do not cover the overall expenses incurred by the care of our dogs, but they do help defray the costs involved.  We thank you for your support. 

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always try to select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dog’s needs and try to find the best match for both dog and human. 
We leave a dog’s profile online until either it has been adopted, has received several applications, or is not able to be adopted for some reason.

animal.description: The name is Habibi and I need to set the record straight. I may have been picked up as a stray, but I wasn’t “astray”… Have you ever heard the saying “Not all who wander are lost”? Well, that is my case exactly! I am on the search for the best thing I could ever ask for: a forever family. Word on the doggy grapevine is that this is the place to make it happen. So I was hoping to wander my way here to FDNLS, and thankfully I was able to hitch a flight, all the way from Maui! Can you believe my luck? So here I am, and Habibi is looking for love! I get along well with all the other dogs here, but tell those pesky cats, no way! I'm working on my crate training here and will need to continue working on it and my basics in my new home. As long as your little ones aren’t tail-tuggers, I think I could get along just fine in a family with kids! I do have arthritis so I like to be treated gently. Now maybe you would consider having me wander into your life?

animal.description: It is a hard lot being the gentle giant…. People sometimes expect so much from me, good thing I can meet their standards. You know, all I really want is to be loved…and to give love in return. Have someone give me comfort and stability. People like to assume that because of my size I am overbearing and oafish. But I am really just a laid-back guy who likes head scratches and long walks with my people. Don’t get me wrong, I’ve got some brute strength that you mostly see when I’m on leash…so a good walking harness will really come in handy! I'll do great in a home with sturdy children or other dogs, but cats and I just don’t get along. I know crate training well and love to have my own little den to call my own. Step up to do battle with me, little David, but cast no stones. Let love be the weapon of choice, and companionship the prize to share.

animal.description:
My name is KravitzI'll go by Lenny, Lovely, The Manhonestly I'd even go by Kid, Hey Lady, or whatever else you come up with as long as you're calling me and you're my peeps! There has been talk since I arrived at the farm about lab mix, hottie (I think I like that one), sweet guy and something about 2 years or so old. Being a happy and flexible guy, I am pleased with just about anything when it involves love and attention. I love to be outside, love to run with friends, and consider most everyone a buddy, people and dogs alike. I am well behaved, don't jump on people, don't bark my head off, and I will let you know when I need to go outside. I would love to have some of my own chew toys, but I won't chew on anything not offered to me. Personal space is not a concept I'm aware of, as my favorite spot is right by your side. I've been total I'm a real couch potato and leaner. Honestly not sure where I learned manners, but I do know how to act like a gentleman they say. When it comes to my crate, happy to wait there or take a nap, I'm easy going that way. I don't know too many tricks, but am happy to practice with some yummy treats. What I really want more than anything is some people of my own, to live with furever. Love, attention, snuggles, and smooches are top on my list for 2021 and everything else is just gravy. I've heard about gravy.can we add that to my list of wishes? Last thing....swear! See you at the farm! Love, Kravtiz

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hi there! My name is Scout.
I am a 8 year old terrier mix. I have lots of love to give and I'm looking for my forever home.

I love people and lots of attention so I would be happiest in a home where my people are home most of the time and can dote on me everyday.

I love to snuggle in bed or hang out on the couch and relax. I enjoy car rides and walks too.

I haven't been around kids much as I lived only with my owner in my previous home. I would most likely be ok with an older respectful child, we would have to meet and see how it goes. I have always been an only dog and prefer that as I can get a little jealous if another dog is around.

I am housebroken, weigh about 25 lbs and know most commands. I will need to be groomed regularly to maintain my handsome look. I am neutered and up to date on my shots.

I would really need a fenced yard as I love to romp around in the backyard and explore all the sights and sounds.

If you're interested in meeting me please fill out the adoption application. Scout's adoption fee is $250 and includes his neuter, microchip, current vaccinations and preventatives plus a free basic obedience course at Cedar Run Pet Boarding & Daycare in Hiawatha. Last Hope requires that all animals be kept as indoor pets only, be altered and current on vaccinations and preventatives. Our adoption process includes reference and background checks, a vet check and a home vist.

She snorts, she snores when she sleeps, she runs around with unbridled joy. She loves toys and loves love more. She has the funniest and sweetest expressions and mannerisms. This girl is so grateful to be alive. Maple most likely had some tough beginnings. She was bred way more than any dog should ever be and shows the remnants of that treatment. She is short and stocky and will probably top out in the 50 lbs range, once she gains some weight. Her face looks as if she is a combination of  a Bulldog and a Pug.

animal.description:
Max is an adorable highly intelligent 4-month-old Border Collie.  He started out life with a wonderful family who were first time dog owners with a small child. Max loved his family and they loved him, so their decision to re-home was a difficult one but ultimately a safety issue (due to resource guarding) and best for Max. 

Because Max has a tendency to herd animals and people, he is better suited for a family with older children and no cats or chickens.  Max has a very high prey drive!  His high prey drive makes him a perfect dog for anyone wanting to excel in herding, obedience or agility.  Without proper training his prey drive can potentially be a safety issue as he has no impulse control over chasing cars and fast moving objects 

He is smart!  Max knows: Go To Your Mat and hold a Down/Stay, Come, Sit, Down, Stand, Touch/Hand Target, Walking Loose in Leash & Leave It.  He knows the cue "Go Potty" when you take him outside to eliminate.

Max is nervous meeting new dogs. He has some food guarding issues (another reason for no small children) that need a savvy owner to continue working on.
Maxi is looking for someone experienced with herding breeds, have a plan for his energy level & Border Collie prey drive, and be committed to continuous consistent daily training.

animal.description:
Say hello to one of the most chill dogs you will ever meet! He's chill with the cats, and he's chill with the dogs, and he's chill with the horses and of course, he's chill with all people. Woody was found in the middle of nowhere probably faithfully waiting for his family to come back for him. It took his rescuer the better part of an hour to earn his trust and save him. Now he's the best pet. He's grateful for meals and minds his manners! He gets along well with everyone and is super easy. His family who dumped him must have quit feeding him and didn't protect his heart from heartworm disease, but the rescue will provide moxi-doxy treatment until he tests negative. He has gained weight and been brought up to date on his vaccinations and will be neutered very soon. He's almost ready to join his forever family and share his faithful and chill personality! Because we are foster based, we require an approved application before a meet and greet can be scheduled. We think that is fair for our fosters so every meet and greet can has the potential to result in an immediate adoption. The application is available on the rescue website and can be completed online.We work with many rescues and strive to find every rescued dog in our care a great home. Sometimes that means transferring that pet to another location where adoption may be more likely. We currently have partners in New York, Pennsylvania, and Vermont.

If you are interesting in meeting any of our pets, the process is to complete an application. It can be downloaded as a pdf document from our website and submitted by email to WindyRidgeRescue@gmail.com as a scanned document or as photos OR can be completed entirely online. Both links are in the header of our website.

Because we are foster based, we require an approved application to schedule a meet and greet. We feel that is fair to our fosters and rescues so every meet and greet can result in an adoption.

We do not have set adoption fees for dogs, but hope adopters will donate generously so we can rescue more. The medical care for every dog can easily exceed the adoption donation. Average adoption fees for dogs in the area range from $175 up to $450.

We ask for a minimum adoption donation of $50 for cats regardless of age. Each cat is up to date on vaccinations, dewormer, and microchipped. Larger donations are always welcome so we can rescue more. Medical care for each cat easily exceeds the minimum donation.

As with every rescue, our resources are limited and the need for rescue help is unlimited. Your generosity helps us to rescue more.

Adopting or fostering for a rescue frees up a space where a new rescue can reside.

If you can't adopt or foster, than please consider donating.

PLEASE READ: Thank you for your interest in one of our adoptable dogs! All dogs listed are still available. If interested, please complete our no obligation application. This can be found at www.waldosmuttleycrew.org. Select the Applications tab, then Adoption Application. THE APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED AND SUBMITTED BEFORE WE CAN START THE PROCESS. It can take up to a week to process an application. We are an all-volunteer rescue so please be patient.

Our adoption area is limited to a 4 hour radius of Indianapolis. We try our best to provide all information in our bios. If you have any specific questions, feel free to ask during the interview process. Some of our dogs have special requirements such as needs another dog in the home or requires a physical and permanent fenced yard. These requirements are not negotiable. Unless otherwise noted, we do not cat test our adoptable dogs. We also require that all pets in your household be spayed/neutered, up-to-date on vaccines and on a monthly heartworm/flea preventative.

E-MAILS: We do not respond to e-mail inquiries without an application. We regret that we cannot respond to every e-mail unless you fill out an application.

All the dogs we offer for adoption have been spayed/neutered, wormed and microchipped, are up-to-date on immunizations, have been tested for heartworm and are currently receiving a monthly preventative. If the dog had additional medical issues, those have also been addressed. Visit our website www.waldosmuttleycrew.org for more information and to complete an application.
Frederick Douglas, a 6 year old rottweiler/beagle mix weighing 55 lbs, is the Belly Rub Connoisseur ... he's gotten it down to a science! He's figured out the exact head tilt to use in conjunction with his soft, brown eyes that will make you stop whatever you are doing and give that belly a rub. Freddie is also adept at contorting himself into the ideal position so you can find the perfect spot! Freddie is such a silly boy! And when you get home, he loves to greet you with a hug and a wagging tail! He loves all people, big & small! Freddie doesn't always realize how big he is so can knock "wee ones" over without meaning to so would probably be too much for kids under 8 years of age. Frederick is submissive & eager to please, so learns quicky. He's an active boy who loves to run & play and would be a great walking companion. He does great with other dogs as well; he's just has a wonderful temperament! However, Fred would not be recommended with cats; he gets too interested in them so we can't guarantee that he wouldn't chase them. He still has occasional accidents so will need a bit more work on potty training. He will require a fenced in yard in his new home so that he has room to run.
We rescued Frederick from a shelter 3 months ago where he was going to be euthanized for space. He had a chronic cough that was not going away despite treatments of various rounds of antibiotics and the use of inhalers. We finally took him to an internal medicine specialist had tests run and have found that Freddie has chronic bronchitis (inflammation of the bronchioles in his lungs). At this point, it's a permanent condition that just means he will always have a cough. He will need to be kept on very low doses of steroids (which are very cheap) for the rest of his life to keep the swelling in the bronchioles down and occasionally may need a cough syrup at times of increased coughing. Other than that, he's a

We adore our Romani! She's so gentle & submissive; and you want to talk a great smile? She seriously grins when she's happy to see you! It'll melt even the coldest of hearts! Romani is a petite 2 1/2 year old german shepherd/border collie mix currently weighing about 40 lbs; we'd like to get another 5 lbs on her as she's still a bit thin. This girl has had a tough life. She was a stray for at least two years; animal control caught her twice during that period but she escaped from them both times. The third time they asked if we would take her. It's amazing that despite spending almost her whole life on the run, she loves the feel of human touch so much! She leans right up against you and snuggles as close as she can get!
Romani is in a foster home with 7 other dogs and co-habitates well with them. Our girl doesn't really engage in play with the others; she doesn't seem to know how sadly. She will lie on the sofa near the others and doesn't mind if they are around her and does like barking at squirrels with them. Romani really needs a home where she can get tons of attention; she craves affection & is happiest when she's being touched so she'd be thrilled to not have to compete with so many dogs for cuddles. Because she can still be a bit timid with new people & new situations, we do feel she would do best with one other confident dog in the home who would show she could cue off to see that everything is safe. Romani will also need at least a 5 foot physical fence as she can easily scale anything shorter. 
Although she is extremely easygoing, we do not think that Romani would do well in a home with small children as she is still fearful of new situations. She needs a calm & quiet environment filled where she can continue to grow in confidence. If you think that you would be a good fit for Romani, please let us know. Her adoption fee is $250; she is spayed, microchipped and current on vaccinations as well as monthly heartworm/flea preventative. Applications are available at waldosmuttleycrew.org . (Indianapolis area)

animal.description:
Hello!  My name is Gretel!  I was saved with my brother Hansel (also up for adoption) from a rural shelter in Oklahoma.   We were strays wandering around and found by a nice lady who cared for us for a few days before bringing us in.  We have lived up to what she said about us!  We are both very dog friendly.  I am about 40 lbs and 1.5 years old.  I love playing and would love a home with another friendly dog to play with.  I also love kids!  We shower them with kisses and of course want to be all over them.  We have met two cats (pretty large cats) and we were more afraid than anything else - (come on -they were big!).  We are very food motivated and take treats gently.  We need to perfect our housebreaking and of course our leash etiquette but overall, we are just awesome young dogs.  We are not bonded BUT could still go together of course.  We love each other but don't NEED each other to survive.  Please email erin@asecondchanceforziva.com for more info!

Looking for a big bundle of love? Buck is your boy!

A young chocolate lab mix, to say Buck is people- and dog-friendly is an understatement. He is instantly best friends with every two or four footed being who comes across his path. There is no cat in his foster home to test out if he is cat-friendly.

Buck is also heartworm negative, kennel trained and largely potty-trained. Not surprisingly, he’s a “velco dog” who wants to be with his people and will keep you company every step of the way.  And he’ll probably have a ball in his mouth while trotting around after you.

Because he’s only 1.5 years old, he’ll need regular exercise and playing to meet his youthful energy level. 

Email info@habitat4paws.org for an application.

**Because we require home visits, we only adopt locally to the Dallas/Fort Worth area. For more on adoption policies, please see the Adopt page of our website, www.habitat4paws.org.

animal.description: I AM ON HOLD PENDING AN ADOPTION APPOINTMENT. Little Lincoln is a handsome 2-month-old boy who currently weighs about 11 pounds. Lincoln's adoption fee is $350 and he is a SHELTER HERO! Which means 100% of his adoption fee goes towards other animals in the shelter. He is neutered and microchipped and has age-appropriate vaccinations. A licensing/microchip fee may apply. To meet Lincoln or to be added to his waitlist, call (505) 983-4309 x 1610 and leave a voicemail message that includes the PUPPY'S NAME, plus YOUR NAME and A GOOD PHONE NUMBER - OR e-mail this information to adoption@sfhumanesociety.org. A scheduler will call you back within 48 hours to confirm your request. If you have other dogs at home, tell the scheduler you would like to bring them along for a Meet n' Greet. SFAS offers a variety of excellent training classes, seminars and Trainer Talks led by animal behavior professionals. These are $50 off for animals adopted from any shelter or rescue group! Due to current COVID-19 restrictions, classes and talks are all presented virtually using Zoom. For course descriptions, schedules and registration, visit https://sfhumanesociety.org/our-programs/behavior-training/group-training-classes/ for classes and https://sfhumanesociety.org/our-programs/behavior-training/special-seminars-and-workshops/ for seminars and Trainer Talks.

animal.description:
***CONSIDERABLE GERMAN SHEPHERD AND/OR OTHER WORKING BREED EXPERIENCE REQUIRED***

Meet Bailey, our happy and spunky senior GSD boy!  Bailey is approximately between 7-8 years old, but he is still full of energy!  Bailey was originally surrendered to our facility in very poor condition.  He was missing most of the fur on his body, and he was severely emaciated.  After bringing Bailey to the vet, it was determined his condition was from extreme malnourishment and a severe flea infestation.  He has since been treated for the fleas and has been eating very well.  In the short time he was with us, Bailey gained a ton of weight from regular feeding and some of his hair did grow back.
He was adopted from our shelter into a great home for a couple months.  Unfortunately, for no fault of his own, Bailey was returned to our shelter.  

Despite what Bailey has gone through, he is still a very loving and friendly dog! Bailey loves getting attention from people!  Bailey is very food motivated and loves treats.  He can be grabby with treats as he was underfed for so long.  Bailey seems to be fine with other dogs, but he is not a fan of cats. 

We are requiring potential adopters to have CONSIDERABLE EXPERIENCE with German Shepherd, and/or other working breeds, to adopt Bailey.  He does seem to listen better to men than women. Bailey can be adopted into a home with another dog pending a meet and greet.  He can go to a home with older children, preferably 13 years old or older.  He is neutered and up to date on vaccinations. Although some of his hair has grown back, Bailey does have Alopecia, and will most likely not grow anymore hair on his body in the spots where he is already bald.  
Bailey is ready for his forever family to take him home and give him the life he really deserves!  If you are interested in adopting Bailey, and have the experience we require, Please Email us at Adotp@savingpawsct.org for more info!

MAC IS OPEN 7 DAYS A WEEK (M-F 8-4pm) (Sat-Sun 10-4pm) Appts to meet dogs can made to suit your schedule, please email/call for an appt. We do prefer to be contacted by email for adoption inquiries at Adopt@savingpawsct.org. The office phone number is  203-235-4179.  Leave a message, and someone will call you back promptly.

You must be 21 years of age to adopt with valid ID. There is a short application for adoption, however if you do not own your home, or you own a condo, we must speak with your landlord or housing association giving permission to dogs/cats. Bully breed specific permission is required if you rent or own a condo. If you own your home, proof of home ownership is required. If there are other pets in the home they must be licensed (if a dog) and up to date on vaccinations. If there is another dog in the home a dog interaction must be done at the shelter before adoption, to ensure the safety and well being of all pets. All children in the home need to be declared and brought down to meet the animal.
Applications must be submitted and approved BEFORE a meet and greet can be scheduled to meet an animal.

ALL ANIMALS ARE SPAYED AND NEUTERED BEFORE THEY GO HOME.
For more info please call 230-235-4179 (Always Leave A Message) or email adopt@savingpawsct.org

animal.description:
Cola was rescued with her 3 puppies from a home with too many outdoor dogs.  She didn't know what being inside was until she arrived at her foster's.

With a guesstimated birthday in Sept. 2018, Cola weighs about 10 lb now.  She's timid, but has warmed up to her foster mom.

**********

April 2020:  We are not holding public adoption events at this time.  Qualified families are being invited to appointments to meet specific dogs.  There are currently no opportunities to view multiple dogs and adoption events aren't being held at Tractor Supply in Lenoir.

Whether dogs / puppies come in as strays or owner surrenders, we usually have to make our best guess as to birthdate and breed.   

If adopted into a home with other animals, particularly cats, your new pet should be crated or secured when you're not available to supervise to insure a harmonious relationship.  

A vet reference is required to confirm responsible pet ownership.  Requirement is a minimum three year vet history documenting current / previous pets are spayed / neutered, kept up to date on core vaccinations, and on heartworm prevention.  We suggest first time pet owners look for an adult dog for companionship and to gain experience through another rescue or your local government-run animal control agency.

Adoption fee covers two vaccinations plus spay / neuter if using our local low-cost spay/neuter clinic (overnight stay required) and surgery occurs as agreed upon in the adoption contract.  Convenience fee equal to refundable spay/neuter deposit may be added if using our veterinarian.  Additional fees for 3rd puppy vaccination, refundable spay/neuter deposit, etc. may apply.  

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

animal.description:
Fourier is a darling little 6 month old, tri-color Chiweenie boy. He is a very outgoing little fella who is very friendly to everyone and gets along with all sorts of people and dogs. He is happy, playful and affectionate. He’d love to have children in his family and a nice fenced backyard in which to run and play with his family. He’s not housetrained yet, but he’s a smart little guy and will pick it up quickly. Fourier is at the perfect age for learning all the behaviors and tricks you would like him to know at your house. 
If you’d like to meet Fourier, the first step is to request an adoption application where it says “Ask About Fourier” and we’ll get the process started. 
Please allow 1-2 weeks to finish processing your application, but please know our volunteers are working hard on it. 
Fourier’s adoption fee is $400 and is tax deductible. 

NOTE: You must complete and submit an application and be approved to adopt prior to being able to meet the dog.  The requested tax-deductible adoption donation is $400 for our puppies, $300 for up to age 7 and $150 for ages 8 and older.
We do not ship our pets.  Be prepared to travel to Tulsa, OK, or Oklahoma City, OK, or the location where this dog is fostered to pick up your dog in person if your application is approved.  Once you are approved, you may adopt any of our dogs that is a good fit. 
We are a non-profit organization that spends our adoption fees and donations on vaccinations, surgeries, various medical tests, medicines, food and supplies needed by our dogs. Our fees do not cover the overall expenses incurred by the care of our dogs, but they do help defray the costs involved.  We thank you for your support. 

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always try to select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dog’s needs and try to find the best match for both dog and human. 
We leave a dog’s profile online until either it has been adopted, has received several applications, or is not able to be adopted for some reason.

animal.description:
Wally is looking for a quiet, adult only, dog experienced home with a yard. 

Wally is a sweet little poodle mix. He is about 4 years old and currently 24 lbs. He is affectionate, playful, quirky and funny. He enjoys going for walks, taking rides in the car and exploring in the yard. He likes to romp around in the house and yard playing tug and chase with his dog buddies. Over time he becomes very bonded to his people and will happily follow them around throughout the day. 

Wally was reportedly neglected during his early years of life. He can be distrustful with strangers and in new situations but has shown he will warm up with slow, gentle introductions and treats. Wally can become overwhelmed with a lot of excitement and noise so a fairly quiet adult only home works best for him. He is most comfortable with calm, firm, positive training and does not do well with harsh discipline. He responds well to leadership, rules, boundaries, routine and affection in that order. When he has a confident person who provides these things he is a delightful, affectionate and happy boy. If he does not receive leadership he becomes confused, insecure, nervous and will display undesirable behaviors. 

Wally is crate trained, house broken and learning to walk politely on a leash. He gets along with other well behaved dogs but needs a cat free home. He enjoys having a friendly, non dominant companion dog to pal around with and keep him company while his humans are away from home. A home where he is not left alone daily for long hours would be ideal. Wally would do well with an experienced dog savvy person who has the time, patience and willingness to provide the leadership, rules, boundaries and structure that he requires to be a sweet, polite, confident, family member. Wally is a little sweetheart who is patiently waiting for his forever home.

Please email right away if you would like to learn more about this dog......and visit our website www.siarescuers.org to learn more about our rescue group.   Adoption fees range from $200-$400 for dogs.  THE DOGS SHOWN ON THE SITE ARE IN FOSTERCARE - WE DO NOT HAVE A SHELTER TO VISIT.  EMAIL is the best way to reach us.We are a volunteer run, very small organization - so please be patient when waiting for a response, but feel free to check back in if you haven't heard from us in a day or so - thank you so much for considering a rescued pooch!

PLEASE READ: Thank you for your interest in one of our adoptable dogs! All dogs listed are still available. If interested, please complete our no obligation application. This can be found at www.waldosmuttleycrew.org. Select the Applications tab, then Adoption Application. THE APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED AND SUBMITTED BEFORE WE CAN START THE PROCESS. It can take up to a week to process an application. We are an all-volunteer rescue so please be patient.

Our adoption area is limited to a 4 hour radius of Indianapolis. We try our best to provide all information in our bios. If you have any specific questions, feel free to ask during the interview process. Some of our dogs have special requirements such as needs another dog in the home or requires a physical and permanent fenced yard. These requirements are not negotiable. Unless otherwise noted, we do not cat test our adoptable dogs. We also require that all pets in your household be spayed/neutered, up-to-date on vaccines and on a monthly heartworm/flea preventative.

E-MAILS: We do not respond to e-mail inquiries without an application. We regret that we cannot respond to every e-mail unless you fill out an application.

All the dogs we offer for adoption have been spayed/neutered, wormed and microchipped, are up-to-date on immunizations, have been tested for heartworm and are currently receiving a monthly preventative. If the dog had additional medical issues, those have also been addressed. Visit our website www.waldosmuttleycrew.org for more information and to complete an application.
Aspen is a beautiful 3 year old redtick coonhound who loves people! She is definitely happiest when she is with her humans so would prefer a home where she isn't left alone for long lengths of time. Aspen really wants to be friends with other dogs but sadly is very lacking in doggy social skills; she just doesn't understand canine language so misinterprets play stances as aggression & runs away or thinks that grumbles of irritation are invitations to play chase. We have been working with her and she is doing so much better. We think she would be best in a home with a large dog who is confident without being aggressive so as to continue showing her how to assimilate into a dog pack (which she desperately wants to do). However, we do think Aspen would do fine as an only dog as well as long as her people were with her most of the time. 
As are most hounds, Aspen is active & will definitely require a physical 5 foot fence. She is a "scent hound" and will follow her nose given a chance. 
Aspen doesn't seem to have had much attention in the past so absolutely melts when you start petting her. If you think you can give her the love she deserves, please let us know. Her adoption fee is $200; she is spayed, microchipped and current on vaccinations as well as monthly heartworm/flea preventative. Applications are available at waldosmuttleycrew.org . (Indianapolis area)

All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, shots current (DHPP, Bordetella and Rabies where applicable), dewormed, flea and tick treated and microchipped.
* If you are interested in a dog, please first read the biography on the dog (keep scrolling down for the bio!) and then go to our website, www.dpsrescue.com for an application. Our adoption fee is $400-$800. Each biography will specifically list the adoption fee.Adoption Fee: $650

Betty's puppies are 11 week old Poodle-Terrier mix puppies who are around 6 lbs each. Mom is about 12lbs and it's reasonable to think these little ones will be under 15lbs when full grown. Mom came into our rescue pregnant. She was a part of a group of 11 dogs who were abandoned and neglected and we took them all in. It's been quite a ride with all of them. And now this little litter is ready to go...

These puppies do not have the non-shedding coat. They will shed. These cutie pies are all incredibly affectionate and playful. However, they all have their own unique little quirks that we absolutely adore. Cremini, with her love of toys and playtime, is the perfect pup for someone who wants a dog to make them laugh. Portobello is super cuddly. She loves to fall asleep in people's arms. Porcini, with his affectionate nature and gentleness, is just the pup for someone who wants a couch buddy. And last but not least, is Enoki. Enoki is super cuddly and has surprising intelligence. Lets just say that whoever gets to take care of any of these puppies is very lucky!

In between napping, snuggling, and eating, these puppies are working on some basic training. They have also established a daily routine with their foster:

"The puppies will usually wake up around 7-8 AM and demand to be let out of their playpen. From there, they run to the potty pads to do their business, and then the kitchen where they eat both canned food and kibble. They'll run around the living room, crawl into the toy box, and wrestle with their mom and our dog Squish. Their favorite game is hide and seek under the coffee table where they'll play fight with each other for hours, then cuddle together, and fall asleep.

They also have their own unique personalities:

Cremini: Cremini is polar-bear white and has the largest floppy ears out of the four. However, on top of her cuteness she also has a playful personality. She loves to wrestle with her siblings and once she finds a toy she likes, she will proudly carry it around the room and show everyone. Too cute! She prefers to play with her siblings and the adult dogs in the house but if everyone is sleeping, she will find herself a toy to chew on. She is also super affectionate and is a sucker for belly rubs. She will roll over every time she sees you to get some scratches.

Portobello: Portobello is beige and the roundest of them all. This "roundness" makes her the ideal cuddle buddy for us humans. While she likes to sleep on her own (away from her siblings) she LOVES to sleep in someone's arms. In addition she has a wonderfully balanced personality of playful and chill qualities. On top of her cuddly nature, she also likes to play rough with her siblings. In terms of training, Portobello is good about always doing her business on the potty pad.

Porcini: Porcini is the most independent from his siblings but the most attached to his mom. He was the third one born and is the only male. He is a little more sensitive than the rest, and will get spooked if picked up too quickly. But once he's in your arms, he will sit still for hours and lick your face if you talk to him. He likes to play chase but tires easily and will find a corner to rest away from his loud sisters. This gentleness and calmness makes him a very sweet dog. He just makes your heart melt!

Enoki: Enoki is the youngest one and kind of looks like a lamb with her curly fur. However, even though she might be the youngest, she does not lack intelligence. She is the only one who knows how to go up and down the stairs and she can climb onto the couch (we're still not sure how she gets up there!) In addition to her intelligence, she is super cuddly. If someone lies on the ground, Enoki will find somewhere comfortable on them or next to them and cuddle up to sleep. Finally, similarly to her siblings, she is very playful. She's very fast and loves to chase after squeaky toys.

Betty's puppies have been living in a home with family dogs so they are dog socialized. They also could be options for cats who are dog savvy and don't mind putting up with the antics of puppies.

The Betty puppies are only options for those who have had a dog in the last three years. This is a requirement not a suggestion. It is not met by petsitting, roommate's dogs and/or family pets that remained in the family home. We believe that puppies need the most experienced homes and that is why we seek this type of home. If there are children they need to be over the age of 8.

Our girl is a 2 year old, short coat, Black And Tan With A Little Merle, 70 pound, love sponge! Ms Jade is great with other dogs (slightly submissive), people of all ages and in particular children. This young lady will need a fairly settled environment due to her past abuse. Despite her past she is open, very friendly and meets strangers very well. Jade enjoys exercise be it, walks, hikes, swims or play, yet she is very comfortable spending the evening laying at your feet. Getting along with all of the dogs at our rescue has been a real strong point for her, she is just very accommodating in her openness and gentle demeanor. We offer full disclosure and hope to make the best matches possible. Please know our adoption fees never cover our expenses. We rely on the generosity of our adopters and supporters to help us help the dogs. Our rescue is only in the business of offering full disclosure to adopters, and expects and hopes to engage your questions and concerns fully. We owe it to the dogs we rescue and all the wonderful families/adopters who might consider welcoming our charges into their hearts and home. Our dogs are waiting for that ideal forever home where they will be cherished as deserving family members. It's sad these second chances are even necessary for these dogs, but we are committed to them and will devote the time and energy to their re-homing, and not just move them to save more dogs. We diligently and responsibly seek good matches, as we don't want to re-home the dog again. These animals have already endured more than they should have, and through no fault of their own. It behooves us to be honest and forthright, and we appreciate the same in return from applicants. It's that winning combination of reciprocal trust and respect that allows for successful placements to be made. Happy adopters translate to happy dogs, and that's our goal!

animal.description:
**BECAUSE WE ARE A SMALL RESCUE WITH LIMITED RESOURCES WE CURRENTLY ONLY ADOPT WITHIN ONE HOUR OF BALTIMORE CITY**

Demure little Lulu is the sweetest girl! She is a Senior Citizen whose favorite past times are curling up in her bed or beside her foster mom on the couch where she can get lots of gentle scratches behind her ears. Lulu loves to go on short walks with her tail wagging the whole time (and wagging double-time when she meets a person or another dog!)  

Like many Shih Tzus, Lulu has been diagnosed with dry-eye and will need eye drops twice a day for the rest of her life. Lulu’s foster mom says Lulu has no problems getting the eye drops and takes them patiently without complaint. Her foster mom also says that she may have limited vision, but she gets around very well once she has checked out a space.

We would like to have Lulu adopted around the Baltimore area. She will come up to date on her shots and microchipped. She is not yet spayed, but we will pay the costs associated with the procedure at a facility we approve of or choose. 

If you are interested in adopting her, please fill out an online application on our website wingsoflovekuwait.com. We will then contact you to conduct a home visit and, once you are approved, a $100 deposit is required.

animal.description:
HI! My name is Toby.  I was brought to AGPR back when I was just a pup.  I got adopted and came back about a year and a half later.  Things got too hectic at my household and I was really hoping for a calmer lifestyle.

I'm crate trained and enjoy being in my "man cave" when I need some time to myself.  I LOVE taking walks and sniffing everything I find along the way.  BUT, there's one thing that scares me - it is things with moving wheels.  We are working really hard to help me get over my fear...I have no issues with cars idling or parked, but moving past me is pretty scary.  Could it be the wheels?

Given that fear, my ideal home would be one with a really big yard away from the road.  Until I get over my fears, walks along a road would not be appreciated.  I'm a lovely boy...I just need someone to help me overcome my fears.

All Great Pyrenees require a fenced-in yard (at least four foot high). If you have questions about the breed or our adoption policies and procedures, please go to our website at www.agprescue.org.  There's plenty of good information about the breed on our website - Pyrs aren't a breed for everyone!

Our adoption application is online: http://agprescue.org/adoption-application/agpr-application-donations/  Please note that we are a small regional rescue organization.  We will consider adopting to families within a four to five hour drive to Richmond, VA

animal.description:
Peanut Butter is a male Lab mix. He is about 2 years old and weighs about 65 pounds.  Peanut Butter is absolutely amazing. He is an active pup that likes to relieve any stress with exercise, and a lot of it. He is ready to hit the pavement or any trail whenever you are. He is also looking for a best friend to spend all of his time with as he doesn’t love to be left alone, but his crate training has been going well and he has been just fine (although a little sad) each time his foster mom has to leave. He starts off a little shy, but if you put in the work (and throw a few treats) he is going to be your best buddy.

No kids under 12, and preferably no other dogs (an introduction would be necessary). Any environment would work - currently living in a busy downtown.

www.lowridersofthewest.org

Peanut Butter’s adoption fee is $375.00 - he is neutered, up to date on all his vaccinations and chipped.

animal.description: Hi, my name is Mrs. Beasley. My foster named me this because I'm a real doll! I'm about 5 years old, 6 pounds and a Pom-Chi mix. Once I warm up to you, I enjoy following you around and doing a little happy dance. An ideal home for me would be a quiet home with no pets or just a single smaller dog or cat. I came from a hoarding situation and did not get enough attention as a young dog so i can be wary of new people. I am potty trained, and will go on a puppy pad, but when I get really excited I leak. Oh my! I'm really working on that. I have learned to enjoy car rides and I'm working on leash training. I can act pretty scared, I guess I am still a bit afraid, but once I am in your arms, I really want affection. I realize I have a way to go to be a perfect companion, but I really do love my people once I get to know them. I need a permanent home with a patient family who will continue to help me grow to enjoy new experiences. I know I can be a great companion to an understanding home. Visit with my foster mom and she can tell you more about my progress.
animal.name: Mrs. Beasley

animal.description:
Abbey is a beautiful and sweet girl that loves people and playing with other pups! Abbey seems to be mid to high-energy. She knows how to sit on command and she does great with other dogs. This loving girl is ready for her forever home! 

The standard adoption fee for a puppy or a dog is $200 which includes  rabies vaccination, at least one round of parvo distemper vaccine and spay or neuter.   ARF will adopt to residents who are out of state but will not furnish transportation.  Here are a few of our adoption requirements:  All adopters will be asked to fill out an  application. Adopters must be at least 21 years old. Renters must show proof that they are allowed to have pets, such as a rental agreement. If there is a pet deposit, please show us the receipt that this has been paid. Be prepared to take your pet home with you - bring a leash for all dogs, regardless of age or size (or a pet taxi for small puppies and dogs) and a pet taxi for all kittens and cats. 

Fill out this form if you are interested in adopting a pet from Animal Rescue Foundation. https://docs.google.com/forms/d/10mHOUH71ulyBm-xh0HZcOGsusvXJxrS3pXQHCz3f-tQ/viewform?edit_requested=true

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Red is a handsome, purebred heeler looking for a home that will provide him with plenty of exercise, stimulation, stability, and routine. He is a typical heeler who thrives with a job; without his needs met, he will become bored, destructive, and resort to unwanted behaviors. These dogs are incredibly smart and need someone with the energy to match theirs! Red has completed a basic obedience class at a local facility and loves to learn new things. He's even welcome back there with his adoptive family to make the transition into his new home go more smoothly! Red's favorite activity in the whole wide world is FETCH! Throwing a ball is the way to this guy's heart of gold. Long walks, consistent training, and games/puzzles are also essential to keeping him his happiest. Red needs a home without children, cats, and prefers to be the only dog. He also needs a human (or two) who are familiar and experienced with working breeds. He is a little reserved when meeting new people and a bit wary of strangers. He is NOT an apartment dog, or one to expect to lay on the couch all day. He IS a hiking buddy, adventure seeker, athletic phenomenon, and SO much fun! He has been passed around between a few different homes and is looking to for a final place to land with some pretty special people. Interested in adopting this pet? Please click the adoption info link for more information. And then click on the 'Online Application' link at the bottom of that page.

animal.description:
Norma has now been with us a little over 5 months - she has come a long way and we believe she is officially ready for her own family. Norma is a special little girl and deserves a very special family. Whomever gives her a chance at a new place to call home will have to be able to give her time to adjust in her new environment. She has now lived/co-existed with multiple other dogs for several months but we believe that she would be much happier as the Queen of the castle ? Other dogs tend to make her feel uncomfortable and she isn't her true self when she has to share confined space with other furry friends. She would love to be someone's one and only and provide as many snuggles as one could want. She has done amazingly well with a routine in her foster home. She LOVES toys, going for walks, car rides, snacks and the occasional pup cup ?

Norma is house trained and crate trained but she would love to be allowed the ability to free roam in her forever home. She doesn't tear things up and does well just hanging out. She also would do well around older/respectful children. 

Norma has been prescribed a monthly medication to help her feel more relaxed and we believe this will be extremely beneficial for her as she transitions into her new. Her new family would need to continue this regimen but there is a possibility she could taper off of it once she's settled in. 

This sweet girl deserves her own family and we are hoping 2021 can give her just that. If interested in Norma you can apply at Www.mispitsandfriends.org

animal.description:
Palomino is a handsome 6 year old Chihuahua mix who is looking for the perfect forever family. Palomino is a shy little guy who will need a very gentle and patient person to show him all the love he so deserves while he learns to trust and come around. Palomino would do best in a calm and quiet home with a single person as he can become very protective of his favorite person. Palomino gets along wonderfully with other dogs and would benefit greatly from another single calm but confident canine in his home. Palomino will likely need training, including house training, in his forever home. Palomino will need a home with a yard, no apartments please. Palomino is a sweet and gentle boy who just needs a very loving and patient family to come along and show him how good he can have it. Palomino is full grown at 11 pounds. He is neutered, up to date on vaccines, microchipped and vet checked. His adoption fee of $220 includes a complimentary vet visit. To potentially adopt him come to our shelter location at 1102 W Hatcher Rd in Phoenix 85021, open Tuesday to Sunday 11am to 6pm. --Covid update: To adhere to CDC guidelines, we are open for adoptions only at a max capacity of 15 people in the building at a time. Masks/face coverings are required. For the safety of our staff and customers, we ask that you practice social distancing, sanitization, and if exposed to Covid-19 or sick to please stay home.--

***Visit our website or facebook page for special events schedules!***

animal.description:
PAWS is currently closed due to COVID-19.  The animals are receiving the same high level of care as always.  During this time, we are taking application over the phone.  Until we can safely to resume normal operations, we will be taking deposits and doing adoptions by appointment only on Fridays and Saturdays from noon until 3.  We know it’s difficult to choose a lifetime companion animal from a picture but it’s been working out well for our adopters and most importantly, for the animals in our care. The financial impact is obvious but we're committed to keeping our community and volunteers as safe as possible and providing the best of care for our animals.  Any donations are greatly appreciated to help PAWS provided that care.  Thank you.

Catahoulas are such smart dogs and this girl is so pretty on top of that too.  Debbie is about 6 months old and will be a medium sized girl when she’s all grown up.  Her adoption fee is $175.


All of our animals are provided with age appropriate vaccinations, spayed/neutered and microchipped prior to adoption. 
PAWS has added the H3N2/H3N8 combo flu vaccine to its shot protocol. Every dog is being vaccinated upon intake, however we urge adopters to get a second flu shot for their new family member to ensure as much protection against the flu as possible.
To meet our incredible dogs and offer them the love they deserve, stop by PAWS on Friday, Saturday or Sunday from 10 - 4 PM, call us at 217-243-7297. We do applications in person or over the phone. You can also see pictures on our Facebook page, PAWS Jackson.  With an approved application, a deposit will hold your new best friend for up to 1 week to allow you time to come to PAWS.  This deposit is not refundable nor transferable.

animal.description:
Hi, I’m Penny. I came from Alabama in a van full of other dogs. It was such a long ride and I was so nervous when I got here. It took me just a few days to get used to people and accept the pats and cuddles everyone wanted to give me. These days I’m behaving more and more like a pup, playing with my foster sibling, zooming around the yard, and playing with toys. They say I am  peppy & playful, curious & sweet.  I still get a little scared sometimes because there’s a lot I haven’t seen or experienced before. I love company and need a little  time to warm up to new noises and people.  I really want to be around people and will love you once I warm up!!   I’ve never had any accidents in the house though, and happily sleep all night in the office with my foster sibling.  I love playing outside in the snow- it one of my favorite things to do!  I can toss a toy in the snow, zoom around the fenced yard and play with the resident dog all day if I could!  Speaking of fences- I need a fenced yard- this whole leash thing is new and it is going to take some time, training and patience to get used to it. And I am the prettiest red ever- seriously gorgeous or so I have been told!!

I am a really sweet, curious and fun dog!  I will greet you with a wagging tail and will love being with you.  I might take a little time to warm up, but I know I’m going to be a wonderful pup for someone.
If you would like to meet Penny, please visit spotslaststop.org and fill out an application.

animal.description:
Biker is not a typical jrt and will need a quiet calm home.

Say hello to Biker, a sweet little cutie who came to JRTRO from Quebec in May, 2020 and has been fostered in Toronto with his foster mom Ann since then. Biker had a wobbly kneecap (technically, a medial patellar luxation) that was stabilized with a pin on September 30th. He is still recovering and has two short, at-home physiotherapy sessions a day to keep his knee flexible. It is possible that he will get some arthritis later in his life (or need further surgery on his knee) since the operation was not performed until he was four. 

Biker is taking two Flexadin Plus chewies a day to help to prevent that. JRTRO had a successful fundraiser for Biker’s operation and we are happy to know that he is now playing more and enjoys enrichment games his foster mom. 

 Biker is not a typical high-energy Jack Russell Terrier. He loves to sleep and to be in his comfy bed. In fact, he prefers to be home and in his bed most of the day. Biker had a dental and his teeth are all squeakie clean. We are hoping that his energy level will increase now as he may have had some discomfort.  

Biker enjoys cautiously chasing squirrels in the backyard and to be there for most of his potty needs during the day. One walk on-leash down the street, just a short block, is enough for him, so that he can check out the neighbourhood for new smells. He is good when he meets other dogs. 

Biker was not potty trained when he arrived last May, which is unusual for an older dog, but he is doing very well now, and his foster mom reports there are few accidents. He is a timid dog and has some fears. He doesn’t like cars and motorcycles (he is fostered in downtown Toronto), but is doing well with treats, which he now prefers to barking at the cars. 

. He should live with adults (older children only), people who are at home all or most of the day to give him company. Another dog in the house is not a good idea for Biker; he needs a quiet, calm environment where he can feel safe. A loving, understanding owner who would never raise their voice to Biker would be ideal. He will reward you with love, affection, and many cuddles!

--------------------------------
Interested? STEP 1: Fill out an application! http://russellrescue.org/adoption/

NOTE: ONLY queries with a COMPLETED FORM will receive a reply due to the volume of requests for info we receive.
---------------------------------

****************************************************************************

Biker is being lovingly fostered in Toronto, Ontario.
Apply to adopt him now: http://russellrescue.org/adoption/

Adoption Fee: $400 for Biker

Please note: FILLING IN THE FORM DOES NOT COMMIT YOU TO ADOPTION, but we cannot start a conversation with you without it. http://russellrescue.org/adoption

AFTER submitting the form we can answer your questions. The application saves our volunteers time and is an important first step for us. It also helps us understand if you could be the right fit for Toronto. 

For complete information about our adoption process please go to our website: http://www.russellrescue.org.

Please note that JRTRO does not place rescue dogs in adoptive or foster homes with resident children under the age of 8 

DUE TO THE NATURE OF JRT'S WE WILL NOT ADOPT JRTRO DOGS INTO HOMES WITH UNALTERED DOGS.

animal.description:
I am affectionately called the "the lioness" by some of the AGPR volunteers.  My name is Winnie and I'm one tough girl.  I may be five years old...maybe six...we don't know.  

My main goal in life is to protect my resources.  My people and property are very important to me.  When I am outside and one of those delivery trucks come up the driveway, I let everyone on the premises know an intruder is coming.  And I let the intruder know not to mess with any of my people.

The funny thing is that once I get to know you, I love you and enjoy being loved in return.  Because I am so protective, I really don't feel comfortable in a home with kids or in a home with an active social life.  My best Pyr friend here at the rescue is Kristoph.  He's a big boy and he knows how to play rough and tumble. But he also knows when to stop.  I love it!

I would love an acre or two (or a hundred) of fenced in land to protect and some humans to love.  No city or the burbs for me.  I'm not a girl who wants to be paraded through a neighborhood meeting lots of other dogs and people.  I know there's the right home for me out there somewhere. Could it be yours?

All Great Pyrenees require a fenced-in yard (at least four foot high). If you have questions about the breed or our adoption policies and procedures, please go to our website at www.agprescue.org.  There's plenty of good information about the breed on our website - Pyrs aren't a breed for everyone!

Our adoption application is online: http://agprescue.org/adoption-application/agpr-application-donations/  Please note that we are a small regional rescue organization.  We will consider adopting to families within a four to five hour drive to Richmond, VA

animal.description:
Winter is about 3 years old, and currently in the low 40lbs range.

She has just arrived in our rescue,  and we will be posting more updates as we get to know her better.
She is naturally a little aloof at first meeting, and can be slightly anxious when getting to know an unfamiliar environment, but given time, will warm up nicely, though she is quite independent in the home (as are many Jindos).
She was likely kept by her previous owners as a mainly outdoor dog, but has, in true Jindo style, shown she is perfectly house trained, and well able to live indoors - which we very much prefer!

She appears to get along with other dogs, but as with any dog to dog introduction, we'd recommend patience, caution and care.
We have not tested her with cats, other small critters, or children yet, but would expect her to have a normally high prey drive for smaller, wild animals (squirrels, rabbits etc) and again, would recommend caution with any introduction (regardless of the dog's breed).

At this stage, she is not terribly food motivated, and needs a patient, confident adopter who can help her navigate new situations (hard, slippery floors, elevators, strange vehicles etc). But she does walk quite well on leash!

Contact us for more information, and visit our website to complete an adoption application form:

www.twodogfarms.com/adopt

Adoption fees are $350.00.

info@twodogfarms.com

animal.description:
Bear is a 7-8 year old small-dog mix (honestly your guess is as good as ours). Deceptively lanky, he's still just a little dude, approximately 3.5 small bananas tall, and just around 20lbs. 

Bear is currently in foster care after receiving a dental, to allow for some rest and relaxation.  And rest and relaxation seem to be Bear's M.O. This guy even came to us with his favorite blanket and green bucket to cuddle up in, which he sleeps in every night. 

Bear is currently bunking with very young kids and two bigger dogs. He is content to coexist with both, though he isn't enamored with dogs who enjoy sudden face-to-face greetings (to be fair, it's pretty rude) and doesn't love his sleep spots disturbed so older kids and other dogs with a mind towards relaxing to the max would likely be the best fit. 

Bear has proven to be very well adapted to the homebody life in his foster home. He has become foster mom's shadow, following her everywhere around the house. He enjoys some good scritches, and will never say "No" to a good lap for a nap. He's had no accidents at all (this could change with an adaptation period in a new home but it is clear he has been housetrained), and is good on leash or in the backyard (where I dare say we may have seen him do a sly zoomie on occasion). He's food motivated (soft food and treats) and knows "sit." He rarely has barked in his foster home (once when someone knocked) and has been left uncrated in his bedroom when alone with no destructive behavior (he took a nap, as he's wont to do).

Overall Bear is a real chill little dude looking for someone who will go all in with his chill little dude lifestyle. We don't think that's too much to ask.

animal.description:
PAWS is currently closed due to COVID-19.  The animals are receiving the same high level of care as always.  During this time, we are taking application over the phone.  Until we can safely to resume normal operations, we will be taking deposits and doing adoptions by appointment only on Fridays and Saturdays from noon until 3.  We know it’s difficult to choose a lifetime companion animal from a picture but it’s been working out well for our adopters and most importantly, for the animals in our care. The financial impact is obvious but we're committed to keeping our community and volunteers as safe as possible and providing the best of care for our animals.  Any donations are greatly appreciated to help PAWS provided that care.  Thank you.

Tyson is right about 11 weeks old and simply adorable.  We know he’s a mixed breed and with those stubby legs, who knows what that mix might be.  His adoption fee is $225.

All of our animals are provided with age appropriate vaccinations, spayed/neutered and microchipped prior to adoption. 
PAWS has added the H3N2/H3N8 combo flu vaccine to its shot protocol. Every dog is being vaccinated upon intake, however we urge adopters to get a second flu shot for their new family member to ensure as much protection against the flu as possible.
To meet our incredible dogs and offer them the love they deserve, stop by PAWS on Friday, Saturday or Sunday from 10 - 4 PM, call us at 217-243-7297. We do applications in person or over the phone. You can also see pictures on our Facebook page, PAWS Jackson.  With an approved application, a deposit will hold your new best friend for up to 1 week to allow you time to come to PAWS.  This deposit is not refundable nor transferable.

animal.description:
Sylvia S is listed as special needs dog because she is blind!

Sylvia is a two month old Labrador blue healer Australian cattle dog supermutt mix. She is two months old in about 10 pounds. She is blind but does very well. She will do better with another dog in the home or someone home most of the time to help her get adjusted to her new home. She is good with other dogs and will be good with older kids. She is working on her leash and potty trainingm good with kids, dogs, and cats. 
Sylvia s have your average puppy personality: silly, goofy, sweet, loving and AWESOME.  Want to adopt me?  
Interested in becoming a forever home for Sylvia S? Fill out our online adoption application: http://www.friendswithfourpaws.org/adoption-form.html This is the first step in our process, and we don't go any further without an application.

Find more adoptable pets, news and information on Instagram @friendswithfourpaws or our Facebook page Friends with Four Paws .

We put a lot of time and energy into processing our adoptions to find our babies the best fit home for them and you.  Please do not submit an application if you are not serious about adopting Sylvia S.
We are so excited to work with you to find you a new forever friend, and Sylvia S the perfect forever home, and appreciate you working with us.  

Our adoption fee is $525. This includes their spay/neuter surgery, full (age appropriate) vaccinations, microchip insertion and registration, deworming, heartworm testing and prevention, flea and tick prevention and travel expenses.

All of our dogs are rescued from local shelters and the general public. Each dog is then placed in a foster home where he/she is kept for quarantine, to ensure if the dog gets sick it can receive proper treatment. We have foster homes in the NJ/NY area waiting to receive their fosters. Once an animal has received an application or there's an adopter interested, we make arrangements for transport. If a dog is already in foster care in NYC/NJ, an adopter will be put in touch with the foster home AFTER an application is being processed.

Thank you in advance for your patience with our process and for making adoption YOUR option!

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to adoptioncenter@homewardtrails.org.

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1. 
For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time. 

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE: http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

This handsome 1 year old guy is Chubs! Found chained, Chubs needed our help. He's a very happy and eager boy who is looking for a family or home with older or no kids. 

Adoption Coordinator: Adoption Center
Location: Adoption Center

The adoption fee for this dog/puppy is $475. This fee includes spay/neuter and microchip. 

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description: We took over fostering Nina from your amazing vet, in order to help her heal from her intensive surgical procedure. Great things: -Nina is super super sweet. Her kisses are soft and she takes food from your hand very gently. -Nina does not bark -Nina is good with dogs (but does not engage in play) -Nina is good with our cat -Nina was good with a friend's child -She is very mellow -She is crate trained -Nina LOVES peanut butter; this will be a good training aid! Areas to work on: -Nina is good with all creatures but does not initiate attention, perhaps due to anxiety -Nina goes to the bathroom outside but is too scared to leave her bed and living room area to walk out on her own. We carry her out to use the restroom but she walks back in the house herself. -Nina is must eat only soft/wet food. -Nina is reserved and cautious but has been willing to play a little with stuffed babies -Nina will likely blossom over time but progress may be slow so a patient adopter/foster would be best. Email PACC.AdoptAFoster@pima.gov to learn more!

animal.description: Moose is a beautiful, calm, sweet little turtle looking for a loving home to help him keep coming out of his shell. When he was young, Moose had little contact with people, so up to now, he's been shy and sometimes aloof. He accepts touch and petting, but given the opportunity, he may move away. He's never growled or shown any type of aggression. Moose is more comfortable with women, housetrained and leash trained. He loves to play, run and frolic with other dogs and to play keep away with his toys! Moose will do best with an owner who has experience in helping undersocialized dogs blossom. Bring your entire family to visit this special boy! Kids age 12 or older.
