animal.description:
Play, snuggle or exercise Dandy is your boy! A young, handsome, playful companion? Well, again, Dandy is your boy!

Dandy is between 9 and 12 months old and we believe he is a lab/shepherd mix. Dandy can be a little nervous at time but if you have a treat, he will be your best friend. Dandy is smart and picking up on everything new! He has quickly learned to sit, down, and crawl. He is almost 100% on Loose leash walking not jumping and being comfortable in a crate. We dont know much about his past but considering new things scare him he will do best with someone that wants to show him the works is a good place and not scary.

Dandy is currently in a foster home with several dogs and one of his favorite activities is to sprint around the yard with them. He is going to do best in a home with another dog to keep him busy! Dandy also lives with cats, small animals, and 3 older children and does well with them - it is recommended he be in a home with older children due to his size. Are you looking for a dog that is a great mix of active, smart, and snuggly? Then you should really apply to adopt then Dandy at pipsrescue.org/adopt

animal.description: True to her name, Honey is a sweet older gal who LOVES her people and is very attentive to them. If you're looking for a mellow yet engaged partner in crime to watch TV with, read to, or to supervise you in the kitchen, Honey is the one! She may be a bit of a diva about her paws touching the snow, but throw some booties on her and she is still eager to run around in the yard and sniff endlessly, or to go on a nice medium-length hike. In classic pittie fashion, Honey can dish out the sass when she "talks" or when she playfully tugs on the leash with her mouth, but at the end of the day she is the most loyal couch potato you could ever possibly dream of. She also already knows several basic commands and is fully house trained. It is important to note that Honey is not a fan of other animals and must be the only pet in the home, but trust us, she's worth it!

animal.description:
Hey there! My name is Bill. I'm about 2 years old and am a happy and silly boy. I came to the UP from Missouri, where I had been found as a dumped off dog at a construction site. When the team moved on, they couldn't leave me behind, so a regular visitor and volunteer (yep - all the way from the UP) brought me to CCHS! Now that I've gotten accustomed to this new place and got all my vet work done, I'm ready to find my new home! 

I'm okay on a leash, but still learning. The staff doesn't know if I'm potty trained, but I don't make messes in my kennel. Some other dogs are okay, but I prefer females that are lower key and not too hyper around me. No cats, please. I would do best in a calmer, adult only home with people who understand that it may take me a little while to trust. But, if you promise me lots of belly rubs, I'll be your best friend soon enough.

**My day-to-day care is sponsored by Jackie Huntoon**

animal.description:
Please keep in mind this is a working breed. They can be a great family dog but will require an extensive amount of DAILY exercise, consistent and ongoing training, and just like any other herding breed will likely nip as a way of "controlling," situations. Herding dogs also will need ongoing socialization with not only dogs, but with people, in and out of the home in order to be more accepting of others versus defensive of property. Please keep that in mind PRIOR to informing us that you want to meet this litter. Your research on any breed is highly important both in the quality of life of this animal but cohesion and happiness of your family. This breed does not fit the parameters of every lifestyle and we want to ensure this breed will fit yours.

animal.description:
Basil is a majestic 2-1/2 year old female Anatolian Shepherd who was surrendered by her owner on January 29, 2021 because the family's circumstances had changed and they were no longer in a position to keep her.

Basil has a cream-colored coat with a very dense texture, a long tail, and a beautiful Anatolian Shepherd face with dark brown 'teddy bear' eyes, chocolate brown shading on her muzzle, and large floppy chocolate brown ears.  

Basil absolutely loves children and is very good with them.  She shared her home with children from 5 years to 17 years old.  Basil does not do well with cats or other dogs.  

Basil was kept indoors and enjoyed short walks with her family each day.  She has been known to 'door dash' and escape from her yard on occasion.   Basil is housebroken.

Though Basil has not attended formal obedience training classes, she has been taught several commands by her previous owners (sit, speak, shake, roll over, mine, jump, and easy).  

This girl epitomizes the oft-used phrase 'gentle giant'.  Basil weighs 81 lbs and walks gently on a leash.

Basil has already been spayed.

Ferdinand is 82 pounds, 3-5 years old, neutered, up to date on shots, and microchipped. Please fill out an application on our website www.goodlif3bullyrescue.org/adoption-application-1 or send an email to goodlif3adoptions@gmail.com if you are interested in Ferdinand.

animal.description:
Sweet Frank is a young, 1.5-yr old Pitt Bull Terrier who recently found himself euth listed in an overcrowded shelter in Texas. With the help of a partnering organization, Muddy Paws was able to bring Frank and 12 other young dogs 900 miles to rescue. Tonight Frankie is safe, warm, and adjusting to his new beginning. He'll be spending the next few days acclimating to his new environment (and climate!) and we'll be posting more information about his personality and furever "wish list" in the coming days! Welcome to rescue, Frank!

Before applying to adopt Frankie, you need to be familiar with your local breed-specific legislation regarding Pit Bulls. Applicants must live within 50 miles of the Omaha/Council Bluffs area. 

The suggested adoption donation for Frankie is $400 We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes. 

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver. 

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months. 

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

At just a year old, this handsome Doberman Pinscher mix named Finn found himself on the euthenasia list in an overcrowded shelter in Texas. With the help of a partnering organization, Muddy Paws was able to bring Finn and 12 other young dogs 900 miles to rescue. Finn is now safe and warm in his foster home but is excited to start the search for his "furever" family. He has the heart of a puppy and loves to play with other dogs and people. Finn even gets along with the cat in his foster home, sometimes he will chase him because he'd like to play. Finn is a big fan of toys and antlers. He is fully potty trained and does not cry in his kennel. When left to free roam in the house he doesn't cause any trouble. After puppy playtime is over, Finn loves to curl up next to his people on the couch. His foster mom describes him as "one of the most well-rounded dogs she has ever met"! animal.description:
This good-looking guy is Sokka, a 3-year old Siberian Husky who recently found himself euth listed in an overcrowded shelter in Texas. With the help of a partnering organization, Muddy Paws was able to bring Sokka and 12 other young dogs 900 miles to rescue. Tonight Sokka is safe, warm, and adjusting to his new beginning. He'll be spending the next few days acclimating to his new environment (and climate!) and we'll be posting more information about his personality and furever "wish list" in the coming days! Welcome to rescue, Sokka!

The suggested adoption donation for Sokka is $400 We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes. 

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver. 

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months. 

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
Barney is ready to be your best buddy!

Hi there! My name is Barney and Im a lively fella who is ready to find my pawfect companion. Im a sweet Chow mix (with an adorable snaggletooth). Im about 9-years old, 40-pounds, and in good health! My vision and hearing arent top of the line, but I get along just fine. Im not neutered yet, but its on my calendar. After spending many lonely weeks at the Bakersfield Humane Society, I was transferred to The Animal Pads care where Ive been loving my time with my foster. Im so thankful for my second chance at life. Now all I need is a special hooman who will love me furever! You may notice my beautiful lion cut, and I got my hair done to help with the matted fur and rash, remnants of shelter life. My skin is much better and I will be a furry legend as soon as hair grows back! Or we could continue with this, rawwwrrrrr!

Im a friendly pooch who adores other doggos. I love playing with my furry foster siblings and keeping them company! I havent met any cats yet, but since Im such a mellow man, I think wed be just fine. My hobbies include following my people around the house, long walks, naps, scratches behind the ears, and just being with you! I love going out in public, hitting the beach, and meeting new people. Its not a ruff life!

Im quickly learning all of the good boy behaviors. I had a few slip-ups in the beginning, but with regular trips outside, I dont have accidents in the house. I do well on the leash and I dont get anxious when left alone. I can get a bit defensive when Im startled or when the vet gets a little too handsy. I might give a little snarl, but with some training, I think Ill get more comfortable & trusting. (Some treats wouldnt hurt either!)

My ideal furever family is one who will give me the love and care Ive always longed for. I think Id do just fine in a mellow or medium energy home. Since I can get startled, I think Id do best with older kids. I would adore having some furry siblings to keep me company, but thats not a deal-breaker. As long as I get lots of love from you, Ill be a happy hound! If youre looking for a sweet companion to be your best bud, adopt Barney! My adoption fee is $200 and that includes spaying/neutering, shots, and microchip. If you want to take me home, please fill out the form on the website here: https://theanimalpad.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Sammy Dean is an approximate 4 year old, 58 pound big baby who thinks he weighs about 10 pounds.    He loves to be loved on and cuddled.  He's laid back and a bit lazy.   He's great with kids and good with other pups, but has to be the dominant male.   Like many rescue pups, he's still a bit protective over his food, but separate feeding stations work.   He enjoys spending time sleeping, cuddling, and sleeping.    He needs a stable home with folks who are willing to pay attention to him and give him the love he deserves.   He's great with kids and is ready to find his very own furever family!   Please open your home & hearts for this special boy!

All our adoption fees include spay/neuter, micro-chip, up-to-date vaccinations, including rabies thru date of adoption. This pup is heartworm positive and is currently being treated with the *slow kill method, approved by his veterinarian, on prevention & on flea/tick prevention. 

*The slow kill method of treatment, simply stated, is a 30 day regiment of  doxycycline followed by a monthly dose of Advantage Multi for 12 months, then retesting.   Most dogs test negative after one year of following this treatment; however, we always recommend that potential adopters consult & follow the advice of their family veterinarian upon adopting any of our hw+ pups.   Although the fast-kill method is still considered the "gold-standard" by the AVA, and may be preferred by some vets; the slow-kill method has proven to be effective in our rescue. The main reason we utilize this method is due to our limited financial constraints and the high number of our rescue pups that are infected.   In the cases of severe infection and if the pup is highly symptomatic, we sometimes use the fast-kill approach instead.   Again, we recommend for you to consult with your veterinarian after the adoption is complete and follow their recommendations.   


In order to be considered for one of our beautiful pups, please go to our website and complete and application: https://www.mustluvdogs.org/adoptable-pets.
Please note that we are a DUE DILIGENCE adoption organization. Part of our approval process requires, among other things:
* Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered.
*The majority, but not all, of our pets require a fenced yard or secure enclosure.  In the case of apartments, we require Landlord approval and designated dog area in complex.
*Verifiable good veterinary history INCLUDING regular vaccination/visits and good Heartworm Prevention history is a MUST!
*Adopter must be able to have time to spend with the pup and be able to provide the pup a safe environment to live.
*ALL our dogs are expected to be primarily INSIDE dogs.  They MUST sleep inside the home.  We truly understand that some folks have working dogs (i.e. farmers, ranchers,etc); however, the majority of our dogs have had a rough life prior to coming to us & we want to make sure that they are showered with LUV & maybe even a bit spoiled for the rest of their lives. 

Other facts are also considered, including whether children or other pets are a good fit with the dog. 

Must Luv Dogs reserves the right to deny any applications that we don't think are a good fit with the pup. Our first & foremost concern is the dog's best interest. It is our MISSION to place them in a home that is a great fit for their needs for a lifetime of luv & being part of a family.
*We will consider adoptions in any area; however, will do not ship or transport puppies under the age of 12 mos. We will ONLY transport an adult dog on a transport approved by MLD, at adopter's expense.
* In order to be affordable and afford every family an opportunity to have a pup of their own, we keep our Adoption Fees low; however, please keep in mind that the fees we charge do not cover all costs for the pup.  Any additional donations are greatly appreciated!

Please note that all of our pets are in private foster homes. In order to reduce any stress or confusion for our pups, we require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meet & greet for any of our pups.  Alternatively, you are always welcome to come meet any of our pups at one of our regular Adoption Events.   Our events are always posted on PetFinder OR on our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/mustLUVdogs.org.

Finally, THANK YOU for considering Must Luv Dogs for your next pet. 

*Most dogs require a fenced area in yard. 
*Apartments okay IF nearby dog park or walking trails (with landlord appoval).
*ALL dogs must be INSIDE dogs and treated a part of family. 
*We are a DUE DILIGENCE Adoption Rescue.  
*Must have good Vet history & Heartworm prevention is a MUST!
*ALL dogs are fully vetted, spay/neutered and microchipped prior to adoption.

FYI:   Even though this pup tested heartworm negative, we provide the following procedural information for your information:  Any of our pups who test HW+ are treated with the *slow kill method of treatment.   The *slow-kill method, simply stated, is a 30 day regiment of  doxycycline followed by a monthly dose of Advantage Multi for 12 months, then retesting.   Most dogs test negative after one year of following this treatment; however, we always recommend that potential adopters consult & follow the advice of their family veterinarian upon adopting any of our hw+ pups.   Although the fast-kill method is still considered the "gold-standard" by the AVA, and may be preferred by some vets; the slow-kill method has proven to be effective in our rescue. The main reason we utilize this method is due to our limited financial constraints and the high number of our rescue pups that are infected.   In the cases of severe infection and if the pup is highly symptomatic, we sometimes use the fast-kill approach instead.   Again, we recommend for you to consult with your veterinarian after the adoption is complete and follow their recommendations.

animal.description:
Howdy! Im Pluto.
Oh boy do I have a story for you. Im 10 years old as you can see, and I was recently rescued by the Great Plains SPCA HERO team. My whole life, Ive lived outside on a chain, aside from a few times when the weather was really bad and my previous owner let me come inside. Because of my past living situation, Im a little unsure about this whole new life at the shelter. I was pretty nervous at first, but the staff here were so kind. They gave me time and space to get used to being around humans and being indoors, and I started opening up. When I do get comfortable with you, Ill ever-so-gently paw at you to ask for attention and pets. The humans say its real precious.
Now, I can be uneasy with new people, as you might imagine. The staff here will show you how to go slow with me and give me space to get comfortable. Patience is key. I do know a few commands sit, come and shake to be exact. I am treat motivated and listen to direction well, when its from someone I trust. Im not too sure what those toy things are all about quite yet, but I think Id be happy to learn!
While new people make me nervous at first, dogs are a whole other story! My goofy side comes out when other canines are around. Ive been around small and big dogs at the shelter. Im still learning how to interact appropriately with other dogs, but I definitely show potential. I do think having another dog around would help me grow.
Im just an old boy looking for a new lease on life. Well have some work to do in terms of building my confidence, but itll be worth it in the end! I hope you see that I have potential, just come from a non-traditional past. I hope youll take a chance on a fellow like me.
Love,
Pluto
Requirements:
To ensure that Pluto and the children in your life are both safe and comfortable, Pluto is eligible to go home with children 12 and older. Pluto must meet all family members prior to being adopted.
Medical Information:
Pluto has tested positive for heartworms. Great Plains SPCA covers the cost of confirmatory heartworm testing and general blood work, 30 days of antibiotics prior to heartworm treatment, and the heartworm treatment injections that will kill the adult worms. We ask that as Pluto's new owner, you purchase 6 months of heartworm prevention at time of adoption to partner with us during Pluto's treatment. Heartworm prevention should be given monthly to any dog, but it is especially important for Pluto as it is crucial to ensure they never become infected with heartworms again.

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 9/22/2020
Reason for being in rescue: owner surrender
Foster location: Foster Home in Rocky Mount, NC
Special Needs? Florence is a beautiful dog with an edge. She absolutely requires an experienced rescuer committed to positive reinforcement training. She will not be adopted to a home with children.
Weight: 14 lbs, Florence is overweight and needs to lose at least 2 pounds.
Height: 14 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $299

Fence needed? No

What kind of home would be best for me? Florence requires a home with a very experienced owner. If you have never had your own dog, or have never rescued a dog with behavioral challenges, please do not apply. Florence is not your girl. Florence is in a foster living happily with other dogs and cats. She absolutely cannot be around children. Florence has a lot of love to share with the experienced alpha that will set boundaries, reinforce them positively, and show her lots of positive affirmation.

What is my personality like? The stories Florence could tell! Florence was hit by a car as a young dog. Her owners couldn't afford medical care so they surrendered her to an animal shelter in Georgia. The leg was wrapped and "set" and Florence was adopted out. Thankfully, Florence was adopted by a very experienced owner who recognized that the leg needed attention or Florence would lose it. Off they went to a specialty hospital where Florence had surgery to repair her leg. She slowly healed and recovered. Today you would never know there was anything wrong.

After having her leg repaired, Florence developed a luxating patella in one of her rear legs. Back to the surgeon she went for another surgery and another success. Then in 2018 a CT Scan determined that Florence had a collapsing trachea. She was placed on opiod medicines, but they made no difference. So today Florence has a cough and her physical activity is limited.

In late 2018, Florence's owners started her on Bravecto under veterinary guidance. They only gave her 2 doses, but Florence's behavior changed completely. Whether the behavior shift was due to the preventative is unknown. Regardless, Florence went from being a very sweet and affectionate lap dog to a dog that can have aggressive behaviors.

Florence is as sweet a dog as you will meet 75% of the time. She loves to snuggle, greets you with kisses, and will play with toys happily. But Florence has a switch. You can watch her eyes gloss over and her demeanor change entirely. And when it changes, Florence will snap at you.

Florence needs boundaries. She is not a dog that can sleep in your bed or sit on the couch with you. Yes, she would love to. She would love nothing more. But when you allow her these luxuries, she takes advantage of them and behaves poorly. When Florence has boundaries, her behavior is manageable. She has a very loving heart.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Friendly

Other tips and tidbits: Florence's birthday is 10/16/2012

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire.

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1. 
For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time. 

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE: http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Magic is a shy, sweet girl. In her foster home, Magic has been learning how to be a dog and relax indoors for the first time. She has discovered a love for toys and blankets; she absolutely loves to play with them! She is little miss confident outside where she trots around, rolls in the grass, and barks at all the people and cars going by. She is a treat connoisseur and is determined to try all of them! Bonus: she is housetrained.

Magic has made so much progress, but she is still working on getting completely comfortable around people. She will now happily lay near her foster parents on the couch or bed but still doesn't enjoy being touched by them. She gently takes food from their hands (food really is the way to her heart). She gets extra shy when new people come by, so she keeps her distance from them.

Magic loves having another dog around to show her the ropes. However, she prefers a dog friend that doesn't jump on her and constantly get in her face. A home with small children may not be the best for this same reason. She has also been fine with the resident cat. She needs a fenced yard because she has not mastered leash walking yet, but everyone loves watching her run around and play in the yard!

She is a sweetheart who needs a patient home that will continue to show her that the world isn't scary and she can trust humans. It is clear that she wants human attention and love, but she's still learning how to comfortably receive it.
Adoption Coordinator: Lauren T.
Location: Foster

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. animal.description: Hi there! My name is Max and I am a very active dog, I am a puppy after all. I need LOTS of training. I try to door dash and can sometimes be hard to leash. I also tend to pull a lot on the leash when I walk, the good thing is that I am easy to redirect. I mean what can you expect, I just want to take the whole world in at once. I tolerate the humans touching me all over, so giving me checkups should be easy. I do like to play with humans and will play bow and demand attention by pawing at you when given the chance. When it comes to toys, I do not know what to do with them. I know the squeaky toys and balls grab by attention but aside from that, what is their purpose? Treats! I love my rawhide! Sooo good. Speaking about treats, I am extremely food motivated. I do not know what sit means but I automatically do it because I know it gets me stuff. I will be easy to train if you use those yummy treats. Now... it cannot be all perfect, right? I am not the best when it comes to dogs. I tend to initially bark and lunge at them. It takes me a long time to get used to the other dog and just accept their presence. Once I am familiar with the dog, I will settle down and go back to taking the world in. Staff: Dog tries to door dash, jumps a lot and is hard to leash. Pulls on leash. Is very easily distracted. Toys get his attention but does not know how to play with them. Loves rawhide, allowed for trade off. Was eating food but did not like the hand and stepped back and ignored the food for the rest of the time. Play bows, demands attention by pawing at you. Will automatically sit, does not know commands, will be trainable. Allows you to touch him just fine. Dog-to-Dog: Walked past GSD in the yard on our way to the BA room. Will bark and lunge. Used calm female for test. He initially barked and lunged at her when walking opposite way. Interaction lasted 20-30 mina and the more he saw her, the more he calmed down. Were able to sniff each other, no attempt to bite. He rolled on his back and let female sniff him. Very excited but will calm down to the point where they can be face to face and he will be distracted by something else. Dog-to-Cat: Walked cattery rooms, paid no attention to the cats. When he went inside the room kept sniffing and trying to play w/ the bedding. Once he did see a cat he started whining and play-bowing. Wanted to engage, after the cats hissed and retreated, he kept insisting on playing but was able to direct away nicely.

animal.description:
Clarice was found living in a tent community in the south where she was loved and had lots of socialization with people and other animals. She had her own siblings as playmates and did great with them.

Clarice recently had her own puppies and has been a great mom! Puppies are pretty much spoken for so now it's her turn. 

Clarice's foster says she would be a great dog for a family - she is very sweet and loves to cuddle. She has done great with her foster canine siblings. And she's even co-existing with a cat in home home. 

There are no children in her foster home but we know she was exposed to them in her prior living situation and her foster feels given her sweet nature she would do jus well with kids.

Clarice has not been exposed to a crate and spends time in a separate area of the house while left home without any issues. She has also been housetrained in her foster home. She does well on a leash and does not react to other dogs while walking.

This beautiful mama mama is truly the whole package, affectionate, a great playmate, not a big barker, bonds well with her person. What more could you ask for?

Clarice is heartworm positive and she has started her treatment - don't let that keep you from considering her - we cover the costs and try to have you work with one of our partner vets that hopefully is close to you!!

Name: Clarice
Breed: Terrier/Labrador Retriever
Sex: Female
Age: 1 1/2 yrs (estimate)
Weight: 62 pounds
Spayed/Neutered: Yes
Vaccinations: Up to date
Heartworm: Positive, has started pre-treatment.
Microchipped: Yes

BASED ON OUR OBSERVATIONS:
Good with Children: Yes, saying older children for now. 
Good with Dogs: Yes
Good with Cats: Yes

Adoption Fee: $475.00

IMPORTANT INFORMATION:
Interested in a specific dog, please fill out an application if you are interested in a dog. The number of individual inquiries is overwhelming and we are finding it difficult to respond to each one. We cannot guarantee you will receive a timely response.

Paws New England is a rescue, not a shelter, and as such we do not have our dogs housed in one location - they are in foster homes both in New England and in our southern foster homes. If you're interested in a specific dog, please complete a short online application and you will receive a reply within 48 hours so you can ask questions.

At present, if a dog is listed on our website, the dog is considered still available HOWEVER, may have applications that have come in before yours but it's still too early to know if any are a good match; therefore we encourage you to apply.

NOTICE WITH REGARD TO LOCATION OF DOGS: Please note: Paws New England is a foster-based rescue. We do not have a brick and mortar building to house the dogs we rescue. We have found that dogs in foster homes are much more adoptable because they have been observed in a home setting. Dogs listed with Paws New England typically reside in various locations throughout the south (primarily Tennessee, Texas, and Arkansas) and New England (not necessarily in the state of Rhode Island). You will be notified by the adoption coordinator of the location of the dog you are interested in so you have the ability to decide whether to pursue adoption or not.

Dogs transported to New England are done so at a fee of $150.00 paid directly to the transporting company by Paws New England; no additional transport costs are responsibility of adopter. This fee is included in the adoption donation.

Adoption donations cover pre-adoption vet costs (including vaccinations, spay/neuter when age appropriate, and heartworm testing/treatment when necessary), a microchip, and transportation to New England if necessary.

Donations for our young, healthy puppies and dogs support their fellow canines of advanced age or suffering from injuries and abuse whose donations are reduced but whose veterinary costs are typically much higher. We appreciate your understanding that your dog will help others in need.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

Paws New England abides by the dog importation regulations set forth in the states of MA, CT, NH and RI.

animal.description:
Focaccia is a 2 year old maltese who came from a backyard breeding situation. He was not properly socialized with humans as a puppy, so he is incredibly fearful and is an extreme flight risk. He gets along well with other dogs, but until he feels safe in his home, he will likely not accept love and attention from his humans.

As he is fearful and an extreme flight risk, he will need an experienced adopter who can provide him with the patience, time and structure needed for him to be comfortable in his new home. He is currently working with his foster mom on leash training, as he is afraid of the leash and shuts down when on leash.

He will do best in a home with another dog, so we will only be processing applications from potential adopters who have another, confident dog in the home. As two of the other dogs surrendered with him have escaped on their first day in their new homes, and he is fearful on leash, we would prefer a secure fenced yard for this boy's forever home.

Focaccia's adoption fee will be $385
Please note: We only accept adoption applications through our website or in person (Facebook and Petfinder inquiries are not considered applications).

animal.description:
Dolly is a 2 year old chihuahua mix. She weighs 17.5 pounds, She has a very soft butterscotch colored coat. She was put out of the house by her owner and was living alone in her backyard in the cold and heat for over a year. Very excited to be loved and indoors, she is a very loyal pet. She does not like strangers so we are trying to socialize her. Usually a simple treat is all it takes. She can be dominant when it comes to food and treats but she is learning and can be corrected. She is trained to not go in the house and uses a pet door. The pink on her nose is a healing injury. When we got her it was all scabbed over. Her adoption fee is $275. She comes spayed, UTD and microchipped. please apply at
www.misfitsdogrescue.org

2 yrsMeet Butterscotch! This cutie-pie Labrador Retriever mix is approximately 2 years old and weighs about 54 pounds. He loves to cuddle- but not JUST cuddle, he will nuzzle his head into his foster's neck and groan from the pure joy of feeling safe and close to a human. How is that for dog therapy?! Butterscotch is always happy. He will play with the other dog in his foster home and is dog-friendly, but people are his favorite! He lets his foster parents do whatever they want; he's okay with his paws being touched, tail being touched, messing with his face, squeezing, picking up -everything! Butterscotch is current on his vaccinations, microchipped, heartworm negative, and neutered. Contact
info@rockwallpets.com
for more info or to arrange a meeting with this sweet boy!

Foster Homes Needed!

Do you have time and room in your life for a foster dog?

http://www.muttloverescue.org/foster.html

*****************

Betty came to Mutts from a rural shelter. She is approximately 4 years old, weighs about 45 pounds (could use to gain a little) and is a sweet girl. Betty is new to Mutts and we will update her bio as we get to know her.

**BECAUSE OF OUR REQUIREMENT FOR A HOME VISIT, WE ARE ONLY ABLE TO ADOPT TO HOMES IN THE NORTHERN VA / MARYLAND / DC METRO AREA**

We have adoption events EVERY SATURDAY from 12-3 p.m. Please note that not all dogs can attend every event, so if you are interested in meeting a particular dog, please complete a no-obligation application on our website at http://www.muttloverescue.org/application.html OR write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

Upcoming adoption events:

Mutt Love Rescue is doing everything we can to ensure the health and safety of our volunteers and adopters while continuing our mission to find homes for as many dogs as possible.

Effective immediately, we will not be holding our weekly adoption events. Dogs available for adoption can be met by appointment only. Potential adopters should submit an online application at http://muttloverescue.org/application.html. Once we receive your application, we will contact you to let you know the next steps.

We are always desperate for foster homes, now more than ever. If you are interested in fostering during this difficult time, please complete an application... unless you are a previous adopter/foster, then you can just contact us via phone (703-988-2608) or email (adopt@muttloverescue.org) to tell us which dog you want to foster!

For information on sponsoring this dog, please write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

WE NEED FOSTER HOMES! FOR MORE INFORMATION, PLEASE EMAIL ADOPT@MUTTLOVERESCUE.ORG.

Visit us on Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/muttloverescue
Follow us on Twitter: @Muttlove_Rescue

animal.description:
Bane is a sweet 8-year old male Pit Bull Terrier mix who was surrendered by his owners on January 25, 2021 because they weren't able to give him the proper care that he needed.

Bane has a black short smooth coat with a white bib on his chest, a long tail, and an adorable face with soft innocent eyes that beg for attention, a black button nose, and large semi-erect ears.  This older guy has a very friendly disposition and a lovable personality.  He adored HSOV kennel tech Brad who helped him with his photo session and kept looking to him for reassurance.

The information we were given about Bane indicates that he is good with children and also with cats.  He appears to be ok with other dogs.  Bane is housebroken. 

Bane is cautious around people that he doesn't know, so it takes him a little while to warm up to new friends.

Bane is being listed as a 'Special Needs Dog' since he has a yeast infection on his skin (which is being treated), and he also has some missing hair.  But he is still a beautiful boy in our eyes :)

Bane weighs 58.6 lbs and walks fairly well on a leash.  He will be neutered before being adopted by his new family.

animal.description:
**Please read Nikki's entire profile, which includes a link to the adoption application. Thank you!** 

This gracious lady is Nikki, a 9-year old, 61-pound, Bulldog/Hound mix senior.

Nikki is a sweet, gentle, very laid back, youngish senior. She had a single home with a family since she was a puppy, but their circumstances have changed and they must find a new home for her. 

She has adjusted well to her foster home, becoming a big family favorite. Nikki loves attention, waddles when she walks, prefers to snuggle and take long naps. 

She will be your best friend and follow you everywhere. Nikki has great manners, doesn’t chew on anything and has a huge heart.

Nikki gets along great with other dogs and simply adores everyone she meets. Might as well get some of that love at your house.

All dogs are up to date on vaccinations and spayed/neutered at the time of adoption.  

To adopt or learn more about Nikki, you must fill out an adoption application. To find the application, copy and paste this URL into your browser: WWW.GDRNE.COM/ADOPTION-APPLICATION [Adoption Fee: $425]  **  PLEASE READ: If a dog is listed, then s/he is currently available for adoption. Their information is correct to the best of our abilities and the information we have been given as of the day of posting. Please note, GDRNE does not guarantee the breed of any dog or puppy unless stated that we have run DNA. All breeds listed are educated estimates. Our dogs are rescued from various situations. It is most likely that both their parents were strays and even if not, mixes of some sort and that their grandparents were mixes as well. The dog may have some genetic material of an American Staffordshire Terrier (pit bull). The dogs are usually mixes of many breeds, making them a breed all their own - a True and adorable American MUTT. If you are interested in this dog, you must submit an application. Great Dog is not a shelter so there is no building you can visit. Our dogs live in private foster homes until adopted. To learn more about our *shelterless* rescue, adoption fees, and procedures, review the list of Frequently Asked Questions on our website at WWW.GDRNE.COM.

animal.description: Ozzie is quite the cool guy! He is a seven-year-old male collie with a beautiful sable coat. He loves to get outside for fun walks where he can investigate everything in his path and meet other dogs along the way. He loves to meet other dogs, since he lived with other dogs in his previous home. Around the house, Ozzie loves to just relax! He is content hanging around the couch or inside of his crate. He'll come over and plop his head down on your lap. He is a bit standoffish with new people, so we are seeking a home where he can live with a confident dog and with no children under the age of 16. He is super healthy, but does have a little limited vision in his right eye. He eats well, and will come and sit in order to get "real" food. Ozzie also likes to be brushed. He also does well being left alone in the house. Overall, Ozzie has a real "chill" personality, as nothing seems to bother him! If you are interested in rescuing a collie, please complete this short adoption questionnaire. Our standard adoption fee is $350. This fee helps us to cover the expense of providing each dog with a Health Exam, Rabies/DHPP vaccines, Heartworm Test, Heartworm Preventative, Flea & Tick Protection, Microchip, Neuter/Spay, and a Bath. Thank you for your consideration in adopting a collie in need!!!
